watch the Food Channel?

00:05:41.960 --> 00:05:44.170
Anybody watching the
Food Network here?

00:05:44.170 --> 00:05:45.250
Yeah?

00:05:45.250 --> 00:05:45.970
OK.

00:05:45.970 --> 00:05:48.160
We actually like to watch it.

00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:49.540
It's kind of fun.

00:05:49.540 --> 00:05:54.130
And what's fun is when you give
the same ingredients to, like,

00:05:54.130 --> 00:05:55.750
half a dozen different people--

00:05:55.750 --> 00:05:59.320
and same ingredients,
same amount of time,

00:05:59.320 --> 00:06:04.150
and the result that comes out
of it is vastly different.

00:06:04.150 --> 00:06:04.900
Now, why is that?

00:06:04.900 --> 00:06:06.790
Of course, you can say
skills and so forth,

00:06:06.790 --> 00:06:09.950
but it is fundamentally,
because those ingredients--

00:06:09.950 --> 00:06:12.280
that details matter.

00:06:12.280 --> 00:06:16.450
The way in which the
ingredients get combined.

00:06:16.450 --> 00:06:18.960
And you know, did you
use the right heat?

00:06:18.960 --> 00:06:21.040
Did you did you take
it off the heat?

00:06:21.040 --> 00:06:25.780
30 seconds too soon or too
late, those little details

00:06:25.780 --> 00:06:29.590
make a huge difference
to the final product, OK.

00:06:29.590 --> 00:06:33.850
And that's what I think what's
cool about the Food Network

00:06:33.850 --> 00:06:36.820
and cooking in general.

00:06:36.820 --> 00:06:39.530
Cuisine, it's an art.

00:06:39.530 --> 00:06:42.410
It's not just follow the recipe.

00:06:42.410 --> 00:06:45.070
And so, I think that's
a great analogy.

00:06:45.070 --> 00:06:46.520
I like that.

00:06:46.520 --> 00:06:48.680
