all your specialists, right?

00:07:03.610 --> 00:07:05.200
You have your choir maybe.

00:07:05.200 --> 00:07:07.390
You have your strings section.

00:07:07.390 --> 00:07:09.370
You have your trumpets.

00:07:09.370 --> 00:07:11.230
And I think it's
kind of similar.

00:07:11.230 --> 00:07:14.020
You could have great
individual musicians,

00:07:14.020 --> 00:07:19.450
but if the conductor is not
bringing everybody into harmony

00:07:19.450 --> 00:07:22.340
then you get a cacophony.

00:07:22.340 --> 00:07:25.120
It's not a great result.
So a great orchestra

00:07:25.120 --> 00:07:28.950
is not just a bunch of
great individual musicians,

00:07:28.950 --> 00:07:32.500
but it's the idea that
you're orchestrating--

00:07:32.500 --> 00:07:35.050
there's something
special that emerges

00:07:35.050 --> 00:07:38.860
if you synchronize everybody in
a way-- and you motivate them,

00:07:38.860 --> 00:07:41.740
and you synchronize them,
and something really special

00:07:41.740 --> 00:07:44.230
happens.

00:07:44.230 --> 00:07:46.630
I think that's another
great sort of example

00:07:46.630 --> 00:07:49.360
of what we mean by
system engineering

00:07:49.360 --> 00:07:51.130
in the technical world.

00:07:51.130 --> 00:07:56.610
This idea of a conductor
bringing everybody in harmony,

00:07:56.610 --> 00:08:00.930
