00:37:53.980 --> 00:37:58.074
The next one was a
little subtle question.

00:37:58.074 --> 00:37:59.740
What are the following
attributes should

00:37:59.740 --> 00:38:02.250
a set of requirements meet?

00:38:02.250 --> 00:38:05.460
And I put check marks here
between what were the--

00:38:05.460 --> 00:38:08.740
so there were multiple
correct answers.

00:38:08.740 --> 00:38:11.820
The set of requirements
means multiple,

00:38:11.820 --> 00:38:13.800
an ensemble of
requirements, as opposed

00:38:13.800 --> 00:38:16.590
to just a single
requirement in isolation.

00:38:16.590 --> 00:38:21.300
So, feasible, verifiable,
and unambiguous,

00:38:21.300 --> 00:38:25.830
those three answers are correct
for individual requirements.

00:38:25.830 --> 00:38:29.190
Each individual requirement
should be feasible, verifiable,

00:38:29.190 --> 00:38:30.960
and unambiguous.

00:38:30.960 --> 00:38:32.940
But when you look at
a set of requirements,

00:38:32.940 --> 00:38:36.830
that's when these other
three come into play,

00:38:36.830 --> 00:38:38.530
absence of redundancy.

00:38:38.530 --> 00:38:41.460
So what this means is that
you shouldn't replicate

00:38:41.460 --> 00:38:43.110
the same requirement,
essentially,

00:38:43.110 --> 00:38:47.190
across multiple requirements
in your requirements set.

00:38:47.190 --> 00:38:48.780
And one of the
reasons for that is

00:38:48.780 --> 00:38:51.840
if you change a requirement
then you might miss it

00:38:51.840 --> 00:38:52.910
somewhere else, right.

00:38:52.910 --> 00:38:57.390
This redundancy is-- keep it
as simple, as straightforward

00:38:57.390 --> 00:38:58.950
as you can.

00:38:58.950 --> 00:39:01.380
Completeness, that
basically means

00:39:01.380 --> 00:39:03.630
that the requirements
set that you develop

00:39:03.630 --> 00:39:05.190
should cover all
the requirements.

00:39:05.190 --> 00:39:08.640
You shouldn't have big holes
and missing requirements.

00:39:08.640 --> 00:39:12.060
And then the last point
is absence of conflicts.

00:39:12.060 --> 00:39:14.820
If you have requirements
conflicts, essentially,

00:39:14.820 --> 00:39:19.510
what this means is there's
no feasible solution.

00:39:19.510 --> 00:39:22.440
So if you think
about optimization,

00:39:22.440 --> 00:39:24.450
you have an
over-constrained problem.

00:39:24.450 --> 00:39:26.330
Basically, that's
what that means.

